","1353":"1353","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Brooksby, Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Kirby Mallory, Leicestershire, England":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, Anglie"},"da":{"Abt 1353–1392":"omkring 1353–1392","1353–1392":"1353–1392","1358–1429":"1358–1429","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","1365–Male":"1365–Afdød","1335–1417":"1335–1417","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1323–1392":"1323–1392","1330–Female":"1330–Afdød","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","Abt 1353":"omkring 1353","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Brooksby, Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kirby Mallory, Leicestershire, England":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1353–1392":"circa 1353–1392","1353–1392":"1353–1392","1358–1429":"1358–1429","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1365–Male":"1365–Overleden","1335–1417":"1335–1417","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1323–1392":"1323–1392","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","Abt 1353":"circa 1353","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Brooksby, Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kirby Mallory, Leicestershire, England":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1353–1392":"about 1353–1392","1353–1392":"1353–1392","1358–1429":"1358–1429","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1335–1417":"1335–1417","1380–1416":"1380–1416","1323–1392":"1323–1392","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","Abt 1353":"about 1353","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Brooksby, Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kirby Mallory, Leicestershire, England":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Villiers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villars","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri.","French: habitational name from any of various places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Villiers was born about 1353, in Brooksby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Villiers IV, was 31 and his mother, Joan Pakenham, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Latimer. He died in 1392, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1353–1392":"umbe